<br>
1. A person who is confirmed to be at the top of the aggro list by a large margin, with no one else there.   <br>
<br>
2. A person who has done *zilch* except AE taunt<br>
<br>
3. Then an a careful analysis of what it takes for person #1 to regain aggro.   <br>
<br>
The best way to do this would be to go to one of the &quot;aggro parsing&quot; mobs (i.e Telk/Gozzrem/LTK) while 2 people were of identical faction level (to eliminate the possibility of faction based hate modifiers if they exist).<br>
<br>
One person (rangers are good for this) builds up a good amount of aggro at a range by casting.<br>
<br>
The secon person (warrior) goes in, presses /disc fortitude so as to prevent melee damage causing a health based aggro modifier, then AE taunt, and backs away.<br>
<br>
He stands RIGHT NEXT to the ranger and waits for the disc to end (so that there's no question of an invulnerability modifier to hate aggro, although there isn't on fortitude, just to rid yourself of the question anyhow).<br>
<br>
/con the mob, the warrior will have the attention.   Then begin seeing what it will take for him to lose it.  I hypothesize that it would take no more than a single aggro causing action on the part of the ranger to regain aggro, but that's really the only way to test it in a controlled environment that I'm aware of.<br>
<br>
To try to assign numeric values to certain actions based on other actions (i.e. assigning sitting to be 1200hate, or proximity to be 500 hate) is simply guessing and isn't really accurate enough to draw any conclusions.  I actually think the hate list has 2 parts...Intentionally generated hate (Actions which cause hate) and modifiers (i.e. sitting, etc, which modify your generated number by a given percentage).  Since both are guesses and no one really knows one way or the other, they're not very accurate to base a statement on. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=strikingone>StrikingOne</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 79<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/10/03 2:48:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2984.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ?</span><hr size=1> Or count how many swings the mt takes after a tank from the back ATs during rage <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=frodlin7th>Frodlin7th</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>/cons RED</span><br>  Posts: 339<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/10/03 3:04:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2984.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ?</span><hr size=1> I would disagree that counting swings post AT during rage would be adequate, particularly on a raid le